 Yeesh!

UBS Group AG is planning to cut more than half of Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=
=80=99s 45,000-strong workforce starting next month as a result of the bank=
=E2=80=99s emergency takeover.
Bankers, traders and support staff in Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s investment ba=
nk in London, New York, and in some parts of Asia are expected to bear the =
brunt of the cuts, with almost all activities at risk, people familiar with=
 the matter said.=C2=A0
Staffers have been told to expect three rounds of cuts this year, with the =
first expected by the end of July and two more rounds tentatively planned f=
or September and October, the people added, asking not to be named as the p=
lans aren=E2=80=99t public.
Three months after UBS agreed to buy Credit Suisse in a government-brokered=
 rescue, the full extent of the job cuts is starting to become clear. UBS, =
whose combined workforce jumped to about 120,000 when the deal closed, has =
said it aims to save some $6 billion in staff costs in the coming years.=C2=
=A0
UBS intends to ultimately reduce the total combined headcount by about 30%,=
 or 35,000 people, two of the people said. That=E2=80=99s broadly in line w=
ith an overall reduction of around 30,000 estimated by analysts at Redburn =
in a report on UBS this month.

More than half! One way to think about the financial-services business is t=
hat many jobs involve=C2=A0some combination of marketing and execution. If =
you are a mergers-and-acquisitions banker, part of your job is to advise co=
mpanies on mergers, structure and negotiate deals, etc.; another part of yo=
ur job is going around to companies and pitching them on why they should hi=
re=C2=A0you, rather than another bank, to advise them on their mergers. In =
much of finance these two roles are combined in one job: The banker who lea=
ds the M&A pitch is also the banker who will lead the deal team; the bond s=
alesperson who takes you out for drinks also fills your bond order; the pri=
vate wealth manager who cold-calls you and asks=C2=A0to manage your money a=
lso picks investments for you. What banks are selling is expertise and rela=
tionships, and it=E2=80=99s harder to sell expertise and relationships if y=
ou=E2=80=99re not=C2=A0the expert who will have the relationship. But they =
are different parts of the job, and the bank needs to hire enough people to=
 do both.
If some big investment bank magically vanished, somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0some other bankers at some other bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0would presumably ha=
ve to take over its execution work. There is external demand for that work:=
 Companies do want mergers, institutions do want to trade bonds, private we=
alth does want to be managed, etc., and if a bank vanished its customers wo=
uld have to go elsewhere for those services. Presumably all the bankers at =
all the other banks are reasonably busy already, executing their own work, =
and if a big bank vanished then those other banks would have to=C2=A0hire=
=C2=A0more bankers to take on the additional execution work.
But nobody would necessarily need to take over the vanished bank=E2=80=99s =
marketing work. Companies want to do mergers, so they sit through pitches f=
rom all the leading banks and pick the best one to do their mergers; they w=
ill be fine with one less pitch. When a bank vanishes, its competitors can =
invest=C2=A0less=C2=A0in marketing, because they have one less competitor t=
o market against. In particular, if there are two big Swiss banks, they are=
 going to be pitching against each other a lot, and they will each have to =
employ a bunch of skilled and well-connected bankers to win mandates in hea=
d-to-head competition. If there is one big Swiss bank, that whole problem g=
oes away! You just show up and say =E2=80=9CI hear you want a merger, I can=
 execute it for you, and no one else can=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s all very ti=
dy.
You could imagine a scenario in which UBS bought Credit Suisse and did=C2=
=A0no=C2=A0headcount reductions: It might look around and say =E2=80=9Call =
of our bankers are busy all day doing work that brings in more money than t=
hey cost, and all of their bankers are busy all day doing work that brings =
in more money than they cost, and all of that work is additive, so we=E2=80=
=99re going to keep everybody.=E2=80=9D
You could imagine a scenario in which UBS bought Credit Suisse and fired=C2=
=A0more than everybody at Credit Suisse:=C2=A0It might look around and say =
=E2=80=9Clook, we have good automated systems for trading stocks and puttin=
g private-wealth clients in index funds, now that rates are higher our M&A =
teams have plenty of slack to do more due diligence, and it turns out that =
there=E2=80=99s no marginal cost to doubling the work that we actually do f=
or clients. So=C2=A0we=E2=80=99ll just have our UBS people and systems prov=
ide all the services that Credit Suisse was providing its clients,=C2=A0fir=
e all of the Credit Suisse people, and also fire=C2=A0our=C2=A0people who w=
ere in charge of trying to lure clients from Credit Suisse, since we don=E2=
=80=99t have to do that anymore.=E2=80=9D
The actual answer is apparently halfway in between? That is a slight exagge=
ration; one thing that happened is that a lot of the busiest Credit Suisse =
teams have already moved elsewhere:

While UBS had originally planned to keep the top 20% of dealmakers, in part=
icular those focusing on technology, media and telecoms, many of the top pe=
rforming bankers have already departed or been poached by competitors, peop=
le said. Deutsche Bank AG, Jefferies Financial Group Inc. and Wells Fargo &=
 Co. are among competitors who have snapped up Credit Suisse staff in recen=
t months.
UBS is hoping to retain the majority of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s private ban=
kers, though many have already left, two of the people said.=C2=A0

By the way, this model is=C2=A0oversimplified. In particular, in risk busin=
esses at investment banks, some execution work is not worth doing: If you a=
re trading derivatives that reliably lose money, or making loans to clients=
 who are not creditworthy, you should just stop doing that. In some ways th=
is is a=C2=A0form=C2=A0of marketing: A good way for an investment bank to g=
ain market share is to do trades with negative risk-adjusted returns, becau=
se lots of people will want to be on the other side of those trades.=C2=A0T=
he team at Credit Suisse that   gave synthetic prime brokerage financing to=
 Archegos should just stop, and   it did. One way for UBS to save on headco=
unt is by no longer having to compete with Credit Suisse for deals. Another=
 way for UBS to save on headcount is by no longer doing whole categories of=
 deals that Credit Suisse did (the ones that blew up Credit Suisse). The le=
ss competition there is among big banks, the less any bank will feel the ne=
ed to take dumb risks to win business.

