   =20
      Oh Lordstown
   =20
 =20

In about 2020, a lot of electric-vehicle companies went public in the US an=
d raised money by merging with special-purpose acquisition companies. Some =
general features of these de-SPAC deals were:
=09The EV company was not all that far along in developing a commercially v=
iable vehicle.=09But it gave shareholders=C2=A0projections=C2=A0saying that=
 it would sell a zillion vehicles at huge profits by, like, 2023.=09It did =
not.

It is interesting to consider how that might=C2=A0end.=C2=A0Like, you raise=
 a bunch of money from retail investors to build electric vehicles, you fla=
il around for a while not building electric vehicles =E2=80=A6=C2=A0then wh=
at? Some options:
=09You keep flailing until you run out of money, then stop. You file for ba=
nkruptcy, there=E2=80=99s no money left, there=E2=80=99s no debt (who would=
=C2=A0lend=C2=A0you money?), the shareholders get zero, it=E2=80=99s not gr=
eat but it=E2=80=99s fairly straightforward.=09You stop flailing at some po=
int=C2=A0before=C2=A0you run out of money. You file for bankruptcy,=C2=A0th=
ere=C2=A0is=C2=A0money left, there=E2=80=99s no debt (who would=C2=A0lend=
=C2=A0you money?), you sell whatever assets there are, and you divide up wh=
atever money is left among the shareholders. This is a better outcome than =
No. 1, though perhaps less likely. If you run a company, it hasn=E2=80=99t =
succeeded in making electric vehicles, and it hasn=E2=80=99t run out of mon=
ey, you will be tempted to keep spending the money to try to make electric =
vehicles, even if your chances of success are slim. Quitting while there is=
 money left and giving it back to the shareholders is better for them, but =
psychologically difficult for you.=09Same as No. 2, but with a subtle disti=
nction. You don=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0debt=C2=A0per se (who would=C2=A0lend=
=C2=A0you money?), but you do have some big liabilities. The liabilities ar=
e: The people who bought your stock in the de-SPAC deal, who believed your =
projections about selling a zillion vehicles at huge profits, probably=C2=
=A0sued=C2=A0you at some point after you started missing projections and th=
e stock started dropping. There is a securities-fraud shareholder class act=
ion. The US Securities and Exchange Commission also probably took an intere=
st in those projections. You file for bankruptcy, you have some assets, you=
 sell them for some money, and then a court has to figure out (1) how much =
of the money goes to the SEC, (2) how much goes to the (current and former)=
=C2=A0shareholders who=C2=A0sued=C2=A0you for fraud and (3) how much is lef=
t over for your=C2=A0current shareholders.

So here is the August 2020 investor presentation from electric-pickup-truck=
 company Lordstown Motors Corp.=E2=80=99s de-SPAC merger, projecting that i=
t would be in =E2=80=9Cfull production=E2=80=9D by the second half of 2021,=
 that it would deliver 31,600 vehicles in 2022 and 65,000 in 2023, and that=
 it =E2=80=9Chas already received ~27k orders (average order size of ~300 t=
rucks) before the first vehicle has been produced, representing potential r=
evenue sufficient to cover 2021 production and into 2022.=E2=80=9D In fact =
Lordstown has produced=C2=A065 trucks=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0not 65,000, just =
65 =E2=80=94 in its entire history through yesterday, and its former chief =
executive officer resigned in 2021 when it turned out that many of those pr=
e-orders were fake.
But Lordstown did manage to raise about $780 million from investors in the =
SPAC and from institutional investors in a parallel private investment in p=
ublic equity deal. It spent a surprisingly large amount of that money =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and of other cash that it raised, including by selling a factor=
y to Foxconn Technology Group and getting some equity investment from Foxco=
nn =E2=80=94=C2=A0on building its 65 trucks; its losses from operations ove=
r the last three years total $890 million, or about $13.7 million per truck=
. (=E2=80=9CAnticipated [bill of materials]=C2=A0costs were approximately $=
42,000 per vehicle for manufacturing in 2021,=E2=80=9D says Lordstown, whic=
h =E2=80=9Ccompared favorably to the Company=E2=80=99s anticipated selling =
price of $52,500 for the Endurance.=E2=80=9D) But it still has money left: =
As of yesterday, it =E2=80=9Chas approximately $136 million in cash on hand=
=E2=80=9D and no funded debt.
But yesterday Lordstown filed for bankruptcy, and I have been quoting from =
the first-day declaration in that case. There is no debt to restructure, so=
 the bankruptcy is not about that. There are some assets to sell =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0its December 2022 balance sheet shows $194 million of property, plant=
 and equipment =E2=80=94 and Lordstown plans to run a sale process for its =
business, but don=E2=80=99t get too excited:
The Company does not believe that capital from other sources is available. =
In September 2021, the Company retained Jefferies LLC (=E2=80=9CJefferies=
=E2=80=9D) to explore all market alternatives. Through that process, the Co=
mpany and Jefferies, in consultation with Foxconn, prepared a list of more =
than 50 potential investors and strategic=C2=A0OEM partners across the glob=
e to be contacted. Jefferies, the Company and Foxconn allocated responsibil=
ity to contact the potential investors and strategic OEM partners based upo=
n who had the best relationship with the most relevant person at those comp=
anies. While the Company, its advisors, and potential partners held numerou=
s meetings and in-person evaluations of the Endurance, as of the Petition D=
ate, the Company has not received any actionable indications of interest.
There is some operating business left, but it loses money, so Lordstown pla=
ns to stop:

Recognizing that it would still require substantial additional funding to e=
xecute its business plan, including scaling the Endurance program and devel=
oping new vehicle programs, the Company has continued to take steps to redu=
ce its cash burn and preserve its assets for the benefit of stakeholders. G=
iven the Company=E2=80=99s current prospects=E2=80=94including Foxconn=E2=
=80=99s unwillingness to honor its funding and product development commitme=
nts and the extremely limited ability to raise capital in the current marke=
t environment=E2=80=94continuing production of the Endurance would only eat=
 away at the Company=E2=80=99s resources. =E2=80=A6
The Company is currently in the process of finalizing a limited number of E=
ndurances still in production. Once that process is complete, the Company i=
ntends to halt production of the Endurance until a value-maximizing transac=
tion is identified in order to preserve its assets and turn its focus entir=
ely to maximizing recoveries through the chapter 11 cases.

Schematically this is a company with about $136 million of cash, some equip=
ment and inventory to sell, no debt, and no operating business. It can just=
 stop, send the shareholders their pro rata share of the cash, and go home.
Well, no, there are two real issues in the bankruptcy. One is that yesterda=
y=C2=A0Lordstown also sued Foxconn, in the bankruptcy court, essentially bl=
aming Foxconn for its failure. In 2021 Lordstown sold its factory to Foxcon=
n and entered into a series of agreements to work together to make electric=
 trucks; Foxconn would supply the components, while Lordstown would supply =
=E2=80=9Ccross-functional expertise in designing, engineering and developin=
g electric vehicles from concept through launch=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Caddit=
ional capabilities in sales, marketing.=E2=80=9D Lordstown=E2=80=99s curren=
t complaint accuses Foxconn of slow-walking and breaching those agreements.
  [1]
 (Foxconn  vehemently disagrees.)
There is also an investment agreement in which Foxconn agreed to buy about =
$170 million of Lordstown stock; it bought some but not=C2=A0all of that st=
ock, and honestly I am sympathetic? I also would not want to buy stock in a=
 company that was sliding into bankruptcy; if I had an agreement to buy tha=
t stock, I would look very carefully at the agreement to see if I could fin=
d an escape hatch.
  [2]
=C2=A0But arguably Foxconn's failure to buy the stock is what tipped Lordst=
own into bankruptcy. Anyway Lordstown is suing over all of this, and I supp=
ose if it wins then it will get either (1) a pile of money to give to share=
holders or (2) a better business deal with Foxconn that it can leverage to =
sell itself for=C2=A0more money to give to shareholders.
But the other issue is the liabilities: Lordstown has no debt, but oh does =
it have lawsuits. Shareholders who believed Lordstown=E2=80=99s hype in 202=
0 had started suing for securities fraud by 2021, and the SEC started an in=
vestigation.
  [3]
 =E2=80=9CThe excitement about [Lordstown=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0innovative techno=
logy and EV aspirations drove its equity market capitalization to reach $5.=
3 billion,=E2=80=9D says the bankruptcy filing, somewhat euphemistically; i=
ts market cap yesterday was about $36 million. If you got excited about Lor=
dstown=E2=80=99s innovative technology and EV aspirations because of its op=
timistic manufacturing plans and fake pre-orders, so you bought the stock a=
t a $5.3 billion valuation and then saw it go down 99%, you might sue for f=
raud, and a class of Lordstown shareholders did.=C2=A0
The bankruptcy declaration says:
The purpose of these Chapter 11 Cases is for the Company to maximize value =
by conducting a robust sale process, reducing its cash burn to preserve res=
ources, and centralizing the claims asserted against the Company to efficie=
ntly resolve those claims and provide meaningful recoveries to its creditor=
s and, if sufficient, its shareholders.=C2=A0
As in any bankruptcy, one goal is to maximize the value of assets, by selli=
ng the company for as much as it can get and by suing Foxconn for damages. =
And as in any bankruptcy, the other goal is to figure out who has a claim t=
o the assets, and divide the assets fairly among those claimants. Here the =
claims are fairly simple, with no debt and limited operations. The question=
 is how much of the money Lordstown has to pay to its former shareholders (=
or the SEC) for getting their hopes up, and how much money it will have lef=
t to pay its current shareholders.

 =20
   =20
      Tokens
   =20
 =20

The current=C2=A0regulatory situation for crypto in the US is that the US S=
ecurities and Exchange Commission thinks that basically all crypto tokens (=
except Bitcoin and a few others) are securities, it keeps arguing this in c=
ourt, and it likes its chances of winning. If the SEC is right, this poses =
all sorts of problems for crypto. Two big ones that we have   discussed a  =
 lot recently are:
=09New crypto projects that want to raise money by issuing tokens have to e=
ither=C2=A0register them with the SEC, which is somewhere between difficult=
 and impossible for token issuers, or sell them under an exemption from reg=
istration, which means roughly =E2=80=9Csell them only to venture capitalis=
ts, institutions and other accredited investors (or non-US investors), and =
lock up those investors so they don=E2=80=99t dump them on retail.=E2=80=9D=
 And existing crypto projects that previously raised money by selling token=
s might get in trouble (and have to pay fines or give back the money) for d=
oing illegal securities offerings.=09Crypto=C2=A0exchanges=C2=A0that want t=
o list tokens (other than a few non-securities like Bitcoin) need to=C2=A0r=
egister with the SEC as national securities exchanges, which is somewhere b=
etween difficult and impossible for crypto exchanges. Though there are   ex=
ceptions here too; a brokerage that intermediates securities trades for its=
 customers might be able to provide a trading venue without being a full-bl=
own exchange, though it will still have to register with the SEC and be sub=
ject to some oversight.

Let=E2=80=99s say that you solve Problem 2, though: You register some tradi=
ng venue with the SEC (as a national securities exchange or alternative tra=
ding system or just a brokerage), and you are allowed to trade tokens that =
are securities. You still have Problem 1: All the securities that you want =
to trade are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0illegal? Illegal-ish? Were issued in unregister=
ed securities offerings?
Well, that strikes me as a fairly manageable problem. Crudely oversimplifyi=
ng, the rule in the US is that if you sell securities to accredited venture=
 capitalists and they immediately turn around and dump them on retail inves=
tors, that=E2=80=99s bad, that=E2=80=99s a public offering of securities an=
d you and the VCs get in trouble. But if you sell the securities to VCs and=
 lock them up for a year, and at the end of the year the VCs dump them on r=
etail, that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s allowed:=C2=A0You=C2=A0sold the =
securities under an exemption from registration (just to the VCs), and=C2=
=A0they=C2=A0sold the securities in a regular secondary-market transaction =
that doesn=E2=80=99t need to be registered.
Again I am oversimplifying the rule, but it is=C2=A0Rule 144, and it is   k=
ind of the standard for how crypto-offerings-that-might-be-securities are c=
onducted in the US these days: You sell to VCs with a long lockup, so that =
the securities offering is exempt. Also it probably helps with trading. The=
  Wall Street Journal reports:

A small brokerage firm thinks it has a blueprint to bring crypto trading in=
to the regulated market.
Prometheum=E2=80=99s plan involves the use of an exemption that U.S. regula=
tors created 50 years ago to permit trading of shares that were restricted,=
 such as those given as compensation to a corporate insider or sold to an e=
arly investor. The exemption is used daily in the stock market to sell mill=
ions of shares.=C2=A0
It has never been used in crypto, however, which developed as an unregulate=
d alternative to Wall Street that still doesn=E2=80=99t have a federal mark=
et overseer. Prometheum, a six-year-old startup with no digital-asset tradi=
ng revenue, has cast its lot with regulators hoping to move crypto onto reg=
ulated exchanges and brokerages. ...
Finding a registered broker who wants to trade crypto assets still doesn=E2=
=80=99t make the tokens themselves free to be traded. That is because their=
 sale was never registered, making their resale restricted just like the sh=
ares given as compensation to CEOs or public-company directors.=C2=A0
Prometheum says the exemption, known as Rule 144, is one way to solve that.=
 ...
Some securities lawyers question whether Rule 144 can be used to trade cryp=
tocurrencies that have been trading on crypto exchanges that don=E2=80=99t =
follow SEC rules. Meeting the exemption=E2=80=99s requirements, including p=
roving that the seller held the asset for at least a year, can be difficult=
 to establish in crypto where trading was meant to be anonymous, said David=
 Adams, an attorney at Goodwin Procter LLP.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAny broker-dealer that embarks down this path is going to be under=
 incredible scrutiny,=E2=80=9D Adams said. =E2=80=9CJust because you are ap=
proved=E2=80=A6that does not mean that goodwill will necessarily continue i=
f you start to list some crypto assets or tokens that the SEC=E2=80=9D does=
n=E2=80=99t agree with, he said. =C2=A0

This is not quite as simple as =E2=80=9Ceven if crypto tokens are illegal s=
ecurities offerings, if you wait a year they become more legal,=E2=80=9D bu=
t that is a=C2=A0little bit=C2=A0what is happening here.

 =20
   =20
      Art vs. fraud
   =20
 =20

Here is a fun art project:
=09I go around on social media saying that I have a clever hedge fund that =
makes returns of 420% per year by trading at nighttime in a multibillion-do=
llar secret market run by foreign central banks and the Illuminati.
  [4]

=09I tell people that if they send me their money I can get those 420% retu=
rns for them.=09You send me your money.=09I keep it.=09You complain.=09I sa=
y =E2=80=9Cno no no, this was an art project, I am pointing out the contrad=
ictions in global capitalism by showing the wild stuff that people believe.=
=E2=80=9D=09You say =E2=80=9Cwell, fine, but give me my money back.=E2=80=
=9D=09I say =E2=80=9Cno keeping your money is what makes it art.=E2=80=9D

Does this work? No? But I have been  obsessed with the  story of MetaBirkin=
s, in which a guy sold digital pictures of what looked like Herm=C3=A8s Bir=
kin bags to gullible crypto/non-fungible-token investors. Herm=C3=A8s sued =
him for copyright infringement, and he argued, no, art project! =E2=80=9CAr=
tistic experiment that examines how society places value on status symbols.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMy MetaBirkins project as a whole was an artistic e=
xperiment to explore where the value in the Birkin handbag actually lies=E2=
=80=94in the handcrafted physical object, or in the image it projects?=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0I  wrote: =E2=80=9CIn some sense anyone who does any scam is ru=
nning an artistic experiment that examines how much money people are willin=
g to give them, but that is not a defense!=E2=80=9D And: =E2=80=9CYou shoul=
d hack his crypto wallet and steal all the money he got for the MetaBirkins=
, and then say =E2=80=98well that too was an artistic exploration of where =
the value actually lies, and I found it, and now it lies in my wallet.=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D
Anyway last week the guy lost in court:

Judge Jed Rakoff, who presided over the case in the U.S. District Court for=
 the Southern District of New York, ordered Rothschild and his associates t=
o abstain from minting or selling MetaBirkins NFTs or using online domains =
associated with the collection. He also doubled down on a jury=E2=80=99s fi=
ndings that Mason Rothschild, the collection=E2=80=99s creator, attempted t=
o mislead consumers about his digital art pieces=E2=80=99 connection to Her=
mes=E2=80=99 luxury bags.
=E2=80=9CAs the jury expressly found, Rothschild, a self-described =E2=80=
=98marketing strategist,=E2=80=99 purposely sought (with some success) to c=
onfuse consumers into believing that his non-fungible tokens (=E2=80=98NFTs=
'), labeled =E2=80=98MetaBirkins=E2=80=A6=E2=80=99 were affiliated with Her=
m=C3=A8s=E2=80=99 iconic =E2=80=98Birkin=E2=80=99 trademarks,=E2=80=9D Judg=
e Rakoff wrote in a filing on Friday.
He added, =E2=80=9CIn effect, the jury found that Rothschild was simply a s=
windler.=E2=80=9D

I mean! A con artist, like a regular artist, is in the business of creating=
 an imaginary world and inviting his audience to share it. I suppose the di=
fference is that a regular artist=E2=80=99s audience knows that the work is=
 imaginary and willingly suspends disbelief, while the con artist=E2=80=99s=
 audience thinks that the work is real and is tricked into suspending disbe=
lief. But sometimes it is hard to tell which is which just from=C2=A0the wo=
rk itself.=C2=A0

