lZGl0LXN1aXNzZS13b3JrZm9yY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZG=
l1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjI4JnV0bV9jYW1wY=
Wlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf369001a" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Yeesh</a>!<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS Group AG is planning to cut more than half=
 of Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s 45,000-strong workforce starting next =
month as a result of the bank=E2=80=99s emergency takeover.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankers, traders and support staff in Credit S=
uisse=E2=80=99s investment bank in London, New York, and in some parts of A=
sia are expected to bear the brunt of the cuts, with almost all activities =
at risk, people familiar with the matter said.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Staffers have been told to expect three rounds=
 of cuts this year, with the first expected by the end of July and two more=
 rounds tentatively planned for September and October, the people added, as=
king not to be named as the plans aren=E2=80=99t public.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three months after UBS agreed to buy Credit Su=
isse in a government-brokered rescue, the full extent of the job cuts is st=
arting to become clear. UBS, whose combined workforce jumped to about 120,0=
00 when the deal closed, has said it aims to save some $6 billion in staff =
costs in the coming years.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS intends to ultimately reduce the total com=
bined headcount by about 30%, or 35,000 people, two of the people said. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s broadly in line with an overall reduction of around 30,000 esti=
mated by analysts at Redburn in a report on UBS this month.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than half! One way to think about the fin=
ancial-services business is that many jobs involve=C2=A0some combination of=
 marketing and execution. If you are a mergers-and-acquisitions banker, par=
t of your job is to advise companies on mergers, structure and negotiate de=
als, etc.; another part of your job is going around to companies and pitchi=
ng them on why they should hire=C2=A0<em>you</em>, rather than another bank=
, to advise them on their mergers. In much of finance these two roles are c=
ombined in one job: The banker who leads the M&amp;A pitch is also the bank=
er who will lead the deal team; the bond salesperson who takes you out for =
drinks also fills your bond order; the private wealth manager who cold-call=
s you and asks=C2=A0to manage your money also picks investments for you. Wh=
at banks are selling is expertise and relationships, and it=E2=80=99s harde=
r to sell expertise and relationships if you=E2=80=99re not=C2=A0the expert=
 who will have the relationship. But they are different parts of the job, a=
nd the bank needs to hire enough people to do both.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If some big investment bank magically vanished=
, somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=A0some other bankers at some other bank =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0would presumably have to take over its execution work. There is ex=
ternal demand for that work: Companies do want mergers, institutions do wan=
t to trade bonds, private wealth does want to be managed, etc., and if a ba=
nk vanished its customers would have to go elsewhere for those services. Pr=
esumably all the bankers at all the other banks are reasonably busy already=
, executing their own work, and if a big bank vanished then those other ban=
ks would have to=C2=A0<em>hire=C2=A0</em>more bankers to take on the additi=
onal execution work.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But nobody would necessarily need to take over=
 the vanished bank=E2=80=99s marketing work. Companies want to do mergers, =
so they sit through pitches from all the leading banks and pick the best on=
e to do their mergers; they will be fine with one less pitch. When a bank v=
anishes, its competitors can invest=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>in marketing, b=
ecause they have one less competitor to market against. In particular, if t=
here are two big Swiss banks, they are going to be pitching against each ot=
her a lot, and they will each have to employ a bunch of skilled and well-co=
nnected bankers to win mandates in head-to-head competition. If there is on=
e big Swiss bank, that whole problem goes away! You just show up and say =
=E2=80=9CI hear you want a merger, I can execute it for you, and no one els=
e can=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s all very tidy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a scenario in which UBS boug=
ht Credit Suisse and did=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>headcount reductions: It mig=
ht look around and say =E2=80=9Call of our bankers are busy all day doing w=
ork that brings in more money than they cost, and all of <em>their</em> ban=
kers are busy all day doing work that brings in more money than they cost, =
and all of that work is additive, so we=E2=80=99re going to keep everybody.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a scenario in which UBS boug=
ht Credit Suisse and fired=C2=A0<em>more than everybody at Credit Suisse:=
=C2=A0</em>It might look around and say =E2=80=9Clook, we have good automat=
ed systems for trading stocks and putting private-wealth clients in index f=
unds, now that rates are higher our M&amp;A teams have plenty of slack to d=
o more due diligence, and it turns out that there=E2=80=99s no marginal cos=
t to doubling the work that we actually do for clients. So=C2=A0we=E2=80=99=
ll just have our UBS people and systems provide all the services that Credi=
t Suisse was providing its clients,=C2=A0fire all of the Credit Suisse peop=
le, and also fire=C2=A0<em>our=C2=A0</em>people who were in charge of tryin=
g to lure clients from Credit Suisse, since we don=E2=80=99t have to do tha=
t anymore.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The actual answer is apparently halfway in bet=
ween? That is a slight exaggeration; one thing that happened is that a lot =
of the busiest Credit Suisse teams have already moved elsewhere:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While UBS had originally planned to keep the t=
op 20% of dealmakers, in particular those focusing on technology, media and=
 telecoms, many of the top performing bankers have already departed or been=
 poached by competitors, people said. Deutsche Bank AG, Jefferies Financial=
 Group Inc. and Wells Fargo &amp; Co. are among competitors who have snappe=
d up Credit Suisse staff in recent months.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS is hoping to retain the majority of Credit=
 Suisse=E2=80=99s private bankers, though many have already left, two of th=
e people said.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, this model is=C2=A0oversimplified.=
 In particular, in risk businesses at investment banks, some execution work=
 is not worth doing: If you are trading derivatives that reliably lose mone=
y, or making loans to clients who are not creditworthy, you should just sto=
p doing that. In some ways this is a=C2=A0<em>form=C2=A0</em>of marketing: =
A good way for an investment bank to gain market share is to do trades with=
 negative risk-adjusted returns, because lots of people will want to be on =
the other side of those trades.=C2=A0The team at Credit Suisse that <a href=
