<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In about 2020, a lot of electric-vehicle compa=
nies went public in the US and raised money by merging with special-purpose=
 acquisition companies. Some general features of these de-SPAC deals were:<=
/p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The EV company was not all that far al=
ong in developing a commercially viable vehicle.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">But it gave shareholders=C2=A0<em>projections=C2=A0</em>sayi=
ng that it would sell a zillion vehicles at huge profits by, like, 2023.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It did not.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is interesting to consider how that might=
=C2=A0<em>end.=C2=A0</em>Like, you raise a bunch of money from retail inves=
tors to build electric vehicles, you flail around for a while not building =
electric vehicles =E2=80=A6=C2=A0then what? Some options:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You keep flailing until you run out o=
f money, then stop. You file for bankruptcy, there=E2=80=99s no money left,=
 there=E2=80=99s no debt (who would=C2=A0<em>lend=C2=A0</em>you money?), th=
e shareholders get zero, it=E2=80=99s not great but it=E2=80=99s fairly str=
aightforward.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You stop flailing at=
 some point=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em>you run out of money. You file for ba=
nkruptcy,=C2=A0there=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>money left, there=E2=80=99s no d=
ebt (who would=C2=A0<em>lend=C2=A0</em>you money?), you sell whatever asset=
s there are, and you divide up whatever money is left among the shareholder=
s. This is a better outcome than No. 1, though perhaps less likely. If you =
run a company, it hasn=E2=80=99t succeeded in making electric vehicles, and=
 it hasn=E2=80=99t run out of money, you will be tempted to keep spending t=
he money to try to make electric vehicles, even if your chances of success =
are slim. Quitting while there is money left and giving it back to the shar=
eholders is better for them, but psychologically difficult for you.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Same as No. 2, but with a subtle distinct=
ion. You don=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>debt=C2=A0</em>per se (who would=C2=A0=
<em>lend=C2=A0</em>you money?), but you do have some big liabilities. The l=
iabilities are: The people who bought your stock in the de-SPAC deal, who b=
elieved your projections about selling a zillion vehicles at huge profits, =
probably=C2=A0<em>sued=C2=A0</em>you at some point after you started missin=
g projections and the stock started dropping. There is a securities-fraud s=
hareholder class action. The US Securities and Exchange Commission also pro=
bably took an interest in those projections. You file for bankruptcy, you h=
ave some assets, you sell them for some money, and then a court has to figu=
re out (1) how much of the money goes to the SEC, (2) how much goes to the =
(current and former)=C2=A0shareholders who=C2=A0sued<em>=C2=A0</em>you for =
fraud and (3) how much is left over for your=C2=A0current shareholders.</li=
>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/31930626.284397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoa=
XZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3NTk1NDYvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIwMDE5NzYzL2VhMTI0ODYzZXg5OS0y=
X2RpYW1vbmRwZWFrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB313dc6d8" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
