NFTs or using online domains associated with the collection. He also double=
d down on a jury=E2=80=99s findings that Mason Rothschild, the collection=
=E2=80=99s creator, attempted to mislead consumers about his digital art pi=
eces=E2=80=99 connection to Hermes=E2=80=99 luxury bags.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAs the jury expressly found, Rothschi=
ld, a self-described =E2=80=98marketing strategist,=E2=80=99 purposely soug=
ht (with some success) to confuse consumers into believing that his non-fun=
gible tokens (=E2=80=98NFTs'), labeled =E2=80=98MetaBirkins=E2=80=A6=E2=80=
=99 were affiliated with Herm=C3=A8s=E2=80=99 iconic =E2=80=98Birkin=E2=80=
=99 trademarks,=E2=80=9D Judge Rakoff wrote in a filing on Friday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He added, =E2=80=9CIn effect, the jury found t=
hat Rothschild was simply a swindler.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean! A con artist, like a regular artist, i=
s in the business of creating an imaginary world and inviting his audience =
to share it. I suppose the difference is that a regular artist=E2=80=99s au=
dience knows that the work is imaginary and willingly suspends disbelief, w=
hile the con artist=E2=80=99s audience thinks that the work is real and is =
tricked into suspending disbelief. But sometimes it is hard to tell which i=
s which just from=C2=A0the work itself.=C2=A0</p>
